WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified software module reference for Adobe After Effects Expressions.
It defines the core expression language (JavaScript/ExtendScript), the
available math functions, wiggle procedural noise, vector math operations,
and the standard timeline-driven variables (time, frame, value). This file
serves as the normative guide for implementing GIOP-compliant motion
graphics and dynamic parameter linking.

WHY IT EXISTS
After Effects expressions are the backbone of procedural animation in motion
design and VFX. Without a canonical reference, different artists use
inconsistent implementations of noise, loops, and easing. This file provides
a single, deterministic specification so that any expression-based effect
can be exactly reproduced in a GIOP pipeline.

HOW IT WORKS
1. Language: JavaScript (ExtendScript) with a set of built-in AE-specific
   objects and functions.
2. Time-based variables:
     time          : current composition time in seconds.
     frame         : current frame number (1-based).
     value         : current property value before expression.
3. Interpolation:
     linear(t, tMin, tMax, valueAtTMin, valueAtTMax)
     ease(t, tMin, tMax, valueAtTMin, valueAtTMax)
     easeIn, easeOut : optional ease-type variants.
   All map input t from [tMin, tMax] to output range, clamped.
4. Trigonometric functions:
     Math.sin(angle)    : angle in radians.
     Math.cos(angle)
     Math.tan(angle)
     Math.atan2(y, x)
5. Procedural noise:
     wiggle(freq, amp, octaves=1, amp_mult=0.5, t=time)
     Generates Perlin noise at frequency freq (Hz), amplitude amp (in
     property units). octaves controls fractal detail; amp_mult scales
     successive octave amplitudes.
6. Vector math:
     add(vec1, vec2), sub(vec1, vec2), mul(vec1, scalar), div(vec1, scalar)
     dot(vec1, vec2), cross(vec1, vec2)  (for 3D)
     normalize(vec), length(vec)
7. Random number generation:
     seedRandom(seed, timeless=false) : sets seed for repeatable randomness.
     random(minVal, maxVal)
     gaussRandom(minVal, maxVal) : Gaussian distribution.

WHERE IT IS APPLIED
- Motion graphics templates (MOGRTs)
- Automated parameter linking across layers
- Procedural animation without keyframes
- VFX pre-comps that require frame-accurate calculations.

WHO USES IT
L2 Engineers building automated After Effects workflows; L3 Compositors
and motion designers using expressions for dynamic content.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Provides a deterministic reference for AE expressions, ensuring that a
wiggle() call with a specific seed produces identical output in any GIOP-
compliant environment. Eliminates ambiguity in vector math and easing
functions.

